They administer at the
federal level, both Medicare

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:46.320
and Medicaid.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:49.190
But just to reiterate,
Medicare is really

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:51.870
mainly a federal thing,
while Medicaid is both.

00:02:51.870 --> 00:02:52.400
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
Yeah, Medicare--

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:54.066
SALMAN KHAN: And
they're run separately,

00:02:54.066 --> 00:02:55.710
so you have Medicare here.

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:56.450
Medicare.

00:02:56.450 --> 00:02:57.589
And then you Medicaid here.

00:02:57.589 --> 00:02:58.630
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah.

00:02:58.630 --> 00:02:59.570
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:00.070
All right.

00:03:00.070 --> 00:03:00.569
All right.

00:03:00.569 --> 00:03:03.290
So let's dive deep
into Medicare.

00:03:03.290 --> 00:03:07.172
So I guess, what is it?

00:03:07.172 --> 00:03:10.040
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: So Medicare
is an insurance program.

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:11.940
It provides insurance
coverage for people

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:12.940
who are eligible for it.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:15.070
So if you're age 67
and over, or if you

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:17.530
have a permanent disability,
a couple other small groups.

00:03:17.530 --> 00:03:20.420
If you have Lou Gehrig's
disease, or end stage

00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:22.722
renal disease, kidney
failure, then you

00:03:22.722 --> 00:03:24.430
can get access to
Medicare too, but those

00:03:24.430 --> 00:03:25.530
are small populations.

00:03:25.530 --> 00:03:28.340
So if you're in those groups,
you're eligible for Medicare.

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.980
Medicare will provide
you with insurance

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:34.870
that will cover hospital bills,
doctor bills, some prescription

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:35.370
drugs.

00:03:35.370 --> 00:03:37.490
It'll cover lots
of medical care--

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:39.740
SALMAN KHAN: You know,
I hear these things--

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:42.380
this is the part that I think
gets confusing for everyone.

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:45.784
Is that you start hearing Part
A, Part B, Part C, Part, D.

00:03:45.784 --> 00:03:47.450
I don't even if those
are all the parts.

00:03:47.450 --> 00:03:49.370
What are those referring to?

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:51.220
And are they exactly
insurance, or are they

00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:52.880
something slightly different?

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:55.680
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: OK, so
Medicare has these four parts.

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:58.040
Part A, Part B,
Part C, and Part D.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:03:59.747
And it can get a
little confusing,

00:03:59.747 --> 00:04:01.830
but we can break it up
into some different pieces.

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:03.996
So the biggest one, in terms
of the number of people

00:04:03.996 --> 00:04:07.400
who are in it, is what sometimes
we call traditional Medicare.

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:10.300
And that's what historically
is Part A and Part B.

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:12.300
And you kind of want to
take those two together,

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:14.210
because they make a package.

00:04:14.210 --> 00:04:16.636
And we call that maybe
traditional Medicare.

00:04:16.636 --> 00:04:18.010
Sometimes people
call it original

00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:20.420
Medicare, standard Medicare.

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:22.420
But when they
passed the program,

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:24.155
when they first
did it, Part A was

00:04:24.155 --> 00:04:26.070
meant to cover
hospital expenditures,

00:04:26.070 --> 00:04:29.690
and Part B was aimed
at doctor costs, costs

00:04:29.690 --> 00:04:31.200
for seeing physicians.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:33.350
Of course, those things
go so closely together

00:04:33.350 --> 00:04:35.720
that nowadays, Part A and
Part B are kind of a pair.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:38.744
So you really rarely would find
someone who only wanted Part A,

00:04:38.744 --> 00:04:39.660
or only wanted Part B.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:39.940
SALMAN KHAN: Right.

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:42.020
Sometimes, you hear the doctor
processes it as outpatient.

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:42.770
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
It's [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:44.311
SALMAN KHAN: Hospitals,
sometimes you

00:04:44.311 --> 00:04:46.460
hear the word inpatient,
means you're living there

00:04:46.460 --> 00:04:47.230
while they're treating you.

00:04:47.230 --> 00:04:49.700
Outpatient, you go visit them
for an hour or two and leave.

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:50.920
And that's where you hear those.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:51.270
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah.

00:04:51.270 --> 00:04:53.512
So that's a way of breaking
up the kinds of services

00:04:53.512 --> 00:04:54.470
that medicine provides.

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:58.645
Medicare actually gets a little
bit-- it's mix and match.

00:04:58.645 --> 00:05:01.510
So really, Medicare
Part A expenditures

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:04.650
when a hospital bills Medicare
for use of the hospital, use

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:06.680
of a room, use of the
services at the hospital.

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:10.337
Anytime a doctor bills Medicare,
even if they saw the patient

00:05:10.337 --> 00:05:12.753
in the hospital, they're going
to be a Part B expenditure.

00:05:12.753 --> 00:05:13.106
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:05:13.106 --> 00:05:13.606
I see.

00:05:13.606 --> 00:05:15.880
So it isn't strictly
inpatient, outpatient.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.020
It really is much more along the
lines of hospital and doctor.

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:20.020
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yep.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:20.686
SALMAN KHAN: OK.

00:05:20.686 --> 00:05:24.005
So I'll maybe put this in
some type of [INAUDIBLE] way

00:05:24.005 --> 00:05:26.340
or something.

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:28.279
It's not necessarily
outpatient, inpatient.

00:05:28.279 --> 00:05:29.320
That's maybe one way of--

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.236
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yes,
it is useful to think

00:05:31.236 --> 00:05:33.709
about that,
outpatient, inpatient.

00:05:33.709 --> 00:05:36.000
SALMAN KHAN: And will it
cover everything that happens?

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:36.912
Including drugs?

00:05:36.912 --> 00:05:37.870
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: OK.

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:40.510
So drugs is one key issue.

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:43.590
To the main question, the
first thing I guess I'd say

00:05:43.590 --> 00:05:46.500
is that traditional Medicare
is pretty comprehensive.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:49.196
It covers most of the things
that people would normally

00:05:49.196 --> 00:05:51.070
encounter in their needs
throughout the year.

00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:51.130
SALMAN KHAN: Right.

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:51.840
Does it cover everything?

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:53.750
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Prescription
drugs is one big exception.

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:55.916
SALMAN KHAN: It does not
cover-- so Parts A and Part

00:05:55.916 --> 00:05:57.400
B do not cover
prescription drugs.

00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:59.490
So when Lyndon Johnson
was signing this,

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:02.640
if Truman had to get
prescribed some drug,

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:06.140
and if he was a Medicare
recipient, in 1965,

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:08.130
he would have had to
pay that out of pocket.

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:09.171
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah.

00:06:09.171 --> 00:06:10.777
So I guess one
caveat I'll note is

00:06:10.777 --> 00:06:13.110
that if you get prescription
drugs that are administered

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:14.620
to you while you're
in the hospital--

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:15.090
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:16.390
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: --you're
staying in the hospital,

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.930
they give you drugs, that's
going to be generally covered

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:20.750
under Part A. It's
when you're outpatient,

00:06:20.750 --> 00:06:23.000
and you're going home, and
somebody sends you to pharmacy

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:23.583
to pick up a--

00:06:23.583 --> 00:06:25.030
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:27.180
Medicare in its original
form would not cover that.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:28.596
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
They would not

00:06:28.596 --> 00:06:30.510
cover the outpatient
prescription drugs.

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:31.920
So that became a
problem for some folks,

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:34.005
and that has generated changes
to the Medicare program.

00:06:34.005 --> 00:06:34.796
SALMAN KHAN: Right.

00:06:34.796 --> 00:06:37.220
Since then, there is a
part now that cover that.

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:37.460
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yes.

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:39.857
So that's the Part D program
as a Medicare extension.

00:06:39.857 --> 00:06:41.440
I don't know how far
you want to get--

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.481
SALMAN KHAN: We can-- I'll
write that right here.

00:06:43.481 --> 00:06:44.600
Well just, D for drugs.

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:45.760
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.843
The whole story of
prescription drugs and Medicare

00:06:47.843 --> 00:06:48.930
has a lot to it.

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:50.510
People would buy
additional policies

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:52.340
if they had A and B.
They'd buy themselves

00:06:52.340 --> 00:06:54.600
a private supplement that
might cover drugs sometimes.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:56.070
But now, with the
new Part D plan,

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:58.150
maybe people would
buy that instead.

00:06:58.150 --> 00:06:59.240
And there's other stuff.

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:00.760
SALMAN KHAN: There's
probably a C right there.

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:01.530
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
There's a C that's coming.

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:02.690
SALMAN KHAN: We can get
to that in a second.

00:07:02.690 --> 00:07:04.260
But so, A and B, traditional.

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:05.550
A, hospitals.

00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:06.620
B, doctors.

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:10.400
And what percent would--
with my health insurance,

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:12.400
there's a copay every
time I visit the a doctor.

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:13.700
It's $20.

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:15.930
How does it work with
traditional Medicare,

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:17.474
with Parts A and Part B?

00:07:17.474 --> 00:07:19.890
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: So if you
just have Part A and Part B,

00:07:19.890 --> 00:07:22.160
then on the Part B
side, doctors are

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.270
covered 80% of the
Medicare allowable charges.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:27.780
So Medicare has a
fee schedule that

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:29.750
governs what doctors can
be paid for services.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:32.500
And Medicare will cover 80% of
that, and the patient pays 20%.

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:33.380
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:34.796
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
For Part A, it

00:07:34.796 --> 00:07:37.964
gets a little more complicated,
but there's a co-payment

00:07:37.964 --> 00:07:38.880
that you have to make.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:40.690
If you go to the
hospital, Medicare

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:42.430
is going to have a
copayment of a fixed

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:44.814
amount, several hundred
dollars, coming up.

00:07:44.814 --> 00:07:45.480
SALMAN KHAN: OK.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:47.230
It's just not as
simple as 80-20.

00:07:47.230 --> 00:07:47.710
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: No.

00:07:47.710 --> 00:07:48.668
Not as simple as 80-20.

00:07:48.668 --> 00:07:51.550
You're going to pay a
copayment there too.

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:53.420
So they're not bad coverage.

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:55.420
But there's certainly
some costs you can run up.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:57.211
And if you're pretty
sick, you might really

00:07:57.211 --> 00:07:58.810
have a bill that's
left [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:00.910
SALMAN KHAN: And there's
extreme flexibility here.

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:03.609
You can see any doctor you want,
go to any hospital you want.

00:08:03.609 --> 00:08:04.650
DR. LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah.

00:08:04.650 --> 00:08:08.650
Medicare Part A and Part B
is, to one way of thinking,

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:11.190
one of the last bastions of
health care as it exists,

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:13.920
or health insurance as it
existed in America in 1965,

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:18.054
'70, '75, when there were really
minimal restrictions on what

00:08:18.054 --> 00:08:20.220
doctors you could see, what
hospitals you could use.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.541
Doctors get lots of discretion
here about the services

00:08:23.541 --> 00:08:26.040
they're going to provide, and
there's not a lot of oversight

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:28.400
that you might see in today's
HMOs, or other kinds of--

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:28.570
SALMAN KHAN: Right.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:30.180
But there are still--
maybe I'm wrong here--

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:32.570
there still are doctors that
won't take Medicare patients?

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:34.028
DR. LAURENCE BAKER:
So, doctors can

00:08:34.028 --> 00:08:36.700
elect to be Medicare
doctors or not.

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:38.387
And some doctors,
