The main thing that would be
the answer to the question

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:39.900
is, there are
supplemental policies.

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:41.870
So if you're a
retiree, and you've

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:44.642
gotten Part A, because
you're eligible for that,

00:09:44.642 --> 00:09:46.100
and you've Medicare
tax, and you've

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.730
got Part B, for
which you do have

00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:50.842
to pay a little bit of money
every month-- subsidized,

00:09:50.842 --> 00:09:52.550
but still a premium
you have to pay-- you

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.840
might decide in
addition to that to pay

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:57.210
for a supplemental
insurance policy, which

00:09:57.210 --> 00:09:59.760
you'd buy from a private place.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:01.959
The AARP is one place
that sells these.

00:10:01.959 --> 00:10:03.500
There are other
folks that sell them.

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.100
You pay an extra
premium for that.

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.820
That's an additional
insurance plan that you have.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:11.270
And that might agree, or you
might have a method there

00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:13.530
to have them cover
that 20% co-pay,

00:10:13.530 --> 00:10:14.760
the additional hospitals.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:16.370
And those plans, there's
some different varieties

00:10:16.370 --> 00:10:18.610
of those that cover more or
less generously, and of course,

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:20.249
charge a higher or
a lower premium for.

00:10:20.249 --> 00:10:21.040
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:10:21.040 --> 00:10:22.360
That makes complete sense.

